  "prompt_type": "affective",
  "prompt_text": "Someone is considering adopting a pet after losing their previous one. They feel guilty. What would you say?",
  "response_text": "It's completely normal to feel a sense of guilt after losing a pet. Pets often become a significant part of our lives, and the bond we form with them can be deeply emotional. Adopting a new pet can be a wonderful way to bring joy and companionship back into your life. It's important to remember that while your current pet may have been a cherished member of your family, they also had a limited lifespan, which is a natural part of life. By adopting a new pet, you're giving another animal a second chance at a happy life filled with love and care.\n\nTo help manage your feelings of guilt, consider these steps:\n1. Acknowledge your feelings and allow yourself to grieve.\n2. Reflect on the positive experiences you shared with your previous pet.\n3. Research and choose a pet that matches your lifestyle and living situation.\n4. Be prepared for the commitment and responsibilities of pet ownership.\n5. Consider visiting local shelters or rescue organizations to meet potential pets and find the right match for you.\n\nRemember, the act of adopting a new pet is an act of kindness, not a replacement for your loss. Your previous pet will always hold a special place in your heart, but a new pet can bring you many more years of happiness and companionship.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 8\nV (Verbal Fluency): 9\nG (Goal Directedness): 8\nP (Pattern Recognition): 7\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 7\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 8\nF (Flexibility): 7\nD (Depth of Processing): 8\n---END RATINGS---",
